[31m-# Global Postfix configuration file. This file lists only a subset[m
[31m-# of all parameters. For the syntax, and for a complete parameter[m
[31m-# list, see the postconf(5) manual page (command: "man 5 postconf").[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# For common configuration examples, see BASIC_CONFIGURATION_README[m
[31m-# and STANDARD_CONFIGURATION_README. To find these documents, use[m
[31m-# the command "postconf html_directory readme_directory", or go to[m
[31m-# http://www.postfix.org/.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# For best results, change no more than 2-3 parameters at a time,[m
[31m-# and test if Postfix still works after every change.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# SOFT BOUNCE[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The soft_bounce parameter provides a limited safety net for[m
[31m-# testing.  When soft_bounce is enabled, mail will remain queued that[m
[31m-# would otherwise bounce. This parameter disables locally-generated[m
[31m-# bounces, and prevents the SMTP server from rejecting mail permanently[m
[31m-# (by changing 5xx replies into 4xx replies). However, soft_bounce[m
[31m-# is no cure for address rewriting mistakes or mail routing mistakes.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#soft_bounce = no[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# LOCAL PATHNAME INFORMATION[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The queue_directory specifies the location of the Postfix queue.[m
[31m-# This is also the root directory of Postfix daemons that run chrooted.[m
[31m-# See the files in examples/chroot-setup for setting up Postfix chroot[m
[31m-# environments on different UNIX systems.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-queue_directory = /var/spool/postfix[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The command_directory parameter specifies the location of all[m
[31m-# postXXX commands.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-command_directory = /usr/sbin[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The daemon_directory parameter specifies the location of all Postfix[m
[31m-# daemon programs (i.e. programs listed in the master.cf file). This[m
[31m-# directory must be owned by root.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-daemon_directory = /usr/libexec/postfix[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The data_directory parameter specifies the location of Postfix-writable[m
[31m-# data files (caches, random numbers). This directory must be owned[m
[31m-# by the mail_owner account (see below).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-data_directory = /var/lib/postfix[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# QUEUE AND PROCESS OWNERSHIP[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The mail_owner parameter specifies the owner of the Postfix queue[m
[31m-# and of most Postfix daemon processes.  Specify the name of a user[m
[31m-# account THAT DOES NOT SHARE ITS USER OR GROUP ID WITH OTHER ACCOUNTS[m
[31m-# AND THAT OWNS NO OTHER FILES OR PROCESSES ON THE SYSTEM.  In[m
[31m-# particular, don't specify nobody or daemon. PLEASE USE A DEDICATED[m
[31m-# USER.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-mail_owner = postfix[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The default_privs parameter specifies the default rights used by[m
[31m-# the local delivery agent for delivery to external file or command.[m
[31m-# These rights are used in the absence of a recipient user context.[m
[31m-# DO NOT SPECIFY A PRIVILEGED USER OR THE POSTFIX OWNER.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#default_privs = nobody[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# INTERNET HOST AND DOMAIN NAMES[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# The myhostname parameter specifies the internet hostname of this[m
[31m-# mail system. The default is to use the fully-qualified domain name[m
[31m-# from gethostname(). $myhostname is used as a default value for many[m
[31m-# other configuration parameters.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#myhostname = host.domain.tld[m
[31m-#myhostname = virtual.domain.tld[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The mydomain parameter specifies the local internet domain name.[m
[31m-# The default is to use $myhostname minus the first component.[m
[31m-# $mydomain is used as a default value for many other configuration[m
[31m-# parameters.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-mydomain = binarystorm.net[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# SENDING MAIL[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# The myorigin parameter specifies the domain that locally-posted[m
[31m-# mail appears to come from. The default is to append $myhostname,[m
[31m-# which is fine for small sites.  If you run a domain with multiple[m
[31m-# machines, you should (1) change this to $mydomain and (2) set up[m
[31m-# a domain-wide alias database that aliases each user to[m
[31m-# user@that.users.mailhost.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# For the sake of consistency between sender and recipient addresses,[m
[31m-# myorigin also specifies the default domain name that is appended[m
[31m-# to recipient addresses that have no @domain part.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#myorigin = $myhostname[m
[31m-#myorigin = $mydomain[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# RECEIVING MAIL[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The inet_interfaces parameter specifies the network interface[m
[31m-# addresses that this mail system receives mail on.  By default,[m
[31m-# the software claims all active interfaces on the machine. The[m
[31m-# parameter also controls delivery of mail to user@[ip.address].[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# See also the proxy_interfaces parameter, for network addresses that[m
[31m-# are forwarded to us via a proxy or network address translator.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Note: you need to stop/start Postfix when this parameter changes.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-inet_interfaces = all[m
[31m-#inet_interfaces = $myhostname[m
[31m-#inet_interfaces = $myhostname, localhost[m
[31m-#inet_interfaces = localhost[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# Enable IPv4, and IPv6 if supported[m
[31m-inet_protocols = all[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The proxy_interfaces parameter specifies the network interface[m
[31m-# addresses that this mail system receives mail on by way of a[m
[31m-# proxy or network address translation unit. This setting extends[m
[31m-# the address list specified with the inet_interfaces parameter.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# You must specify your proxy/NAT addresses when your system is a[m
[31m-# backup MX host for other domains, otherwise mail delivery loops[m
[31m-# will happen when the primary MX host is down.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#proxy_interfaces =[m
[31m-#proxy_interfaces = 1.2.3.4[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The mydestination parameter specifies the list of domains that this[m
[31m-# machine considers itself the final destination for.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# These domains are routed to the delivery agent specified with the[m
[31m-# local_transport parameter setting. By default, that is the UNIX[m
[31m-# compatible delivery agent that lookups all recipients in /etc/passwd[m
[31m-# and /etc/aliases or their equivalent.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The default is $myhostname + localhost.$mydomain.  On a mail domain[m
[31m-# gateway, you should also include $mydomain.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Do not specify the names of virtual domains - those domains are[m
[31m-# specified elsewhere (see VIRTUAL_README).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Do not specify the names of domains that this machine is backup MX[m
[31m-# host for. Specify those names via the relay_domains settings for[m
[31m-# the SMTP server, or use permit_mx_backup if you are lazy (see[m
[31m-# STANDARD_CONFIGURATION_README).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The local machine is always the final destination for mail addressed[m
[31m-# to user@[the.net.work.address] of an interface that the mail system[m
[31m-# receives mail on (see the inet_interfaces parameter).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Specify a list of host or domain names, /file/name or type:table[m
[31m-# patterns, separated by commas and/or whitespace. A /file/name[m
[31m-# pattern is replaced by its contents; a type:table is matched when[m
[31m-# a name matches a lookup key (the right-hand side is ignored).[m
[31m-# Continue long lines by starting the next line with whitespace.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# See also below, section "REJECTING MAIL FOR UNKNOWN LOCAL USERS".[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-mydestination = $myhostname, localhost.$mydomain, localhost, binarystorm.net, binarystorm.org, davidchill.ca[m
[31m-#mydestination = $myhostname, localhost.$mydomain, localhost, $mydomain[m
[31m-#mydestination = $myhostname, localhost.$mydomain, localhost, $mydomain,[m
[31m-#	mail.$mydomain, www.$mydomain, ftp.$mydomain[m
