[31m-# TRANSPORT(5)                                                      TRANSPORT(5)[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# NAME[m
[31m-#        transport - Postfix transport table format[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# SYNOPSIS[m
[31m-#        postmap /etc/postfix/transport[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        postmap -q "string" /etc/postfix/transport[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        postmap -q - /etc/postfix/transport <inputfile[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# DESCRIPTION[m
[31m-#        The  optional  transport(5) table specifies a mapping from[m
[31m-#        email addresses to message delivery transports  and  next-[m
[31m-#        hop  destinations.   Message  delivery  transports such as[m
[31m-#        local or smtp are defined in the master.cf file, and next-[m
[31m-#        hop  destinations are typically hosts or domain names. The[m
[31m-#        table is searched by the trivial-rewrite(8) daemon.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        This  mapping  overrides  the  default   transport:nexthop[m
[31m-#        selection that is built into Postfix:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        local_transport (default: local:$myhostname)[m
[31m-#               This  is  the default for final delivery to domains[m
[31m-#               listed with mydestination, and for [ipaddress] des-[m
[31m-#               tinations    that    match    $inet_interfaces   or[m
[31m-#               $proxy_interfaces. The default nexthop  destination[m
[31m-#               is the MTA hostname.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        virtual_transport (default: virtual:)[m
[31m-#               This  is  the default for final delivery to domains[m
[31m-#               listed with  virtual_mailbox_domains.  The  default[m
[31m-#               nexthop destination is the recipient domain.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        relay_transport (default: relay:)[m
[31m-#               This  is the default for remote delivery to domains[m
[31m-#               listed with relay_domains. In order  of  decreasing[m
[31m-#               precedence,  the  nexthop destination is taken from[m
[31m-#               relay_transport,   sender_dependent_relayhost_maps,[m
[31m-#               relayhost, or from the recipient domain.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        default_transport (default: smtp:)[m
[31m-#               This  is  the  default for remote delivery to other[m
[31m-#               destinations.  In order of  decreasing  precedence,[m
[31m-#               the nexthop destination is taken from sender_depen-[m
[31m-#               dent_default_transport_maps,     default_transport,[m
[31m-#               sender_dependent_relayhost_maps, relayhost, or from[m
[31m-#               the recipient domain.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Normally, the transport(5) table is specified  as  a  text[m
[31m-#        file  that serves as input to the postmap(1) command.  The[m
[31m-#        result, an indexed file in dbm or db format, is  used  for[m
[31m-#        fast  searching  by  the  mail system. Execute the command[m
[31m-#        "postmap /etc/postfix/transport"  to  rebuild  an  indexed[m
[31m-#        file after changing the corresponding transport table.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        When  the  table  is provided via other means such as NIS,[m
[31m-#        LDAP or SQL, the same lookups are  done  as  for  ordinary[m
[31m-#        indexed files.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Alternatively,  the  table  can  be provided as a regular-[m
[31m-#        expression map where patterns are given as regular expres-[m
[31m-#        sions,  or lookups can be directed to TCP-based server. In[m
[31m-#        those case, the lookups are done in a  slightly  different[m
[31m-#        way  as  described below under "REGULAR EXPRESSION TABLES"[m
[31m-#        or "TCP-BASED TABLES".[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# CASE FOLDING[m
[31m-#        The search string is folded to lowercase  before  database[m
[31m-#        lookup.  As  of Postfix 2.3, the search string is not case[m
[31m-#        folded with database types such as regexp: or pcre:  whose[m
[31m-#        lookup fields can match both upper and lower case.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# TABLE FORMAT[m
[31m-#        The input format for the postmap(1) command is as follows:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        pattern result[m
[31m-#               When  pattern  matches  the  recipient  address  or[m
[31m-#               domain, use the corresponding result.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        blank lines and comments[m
[31m-#               Empty  lines and whitespace-only lines are ignored,[m
[31m-#               as are lines whose first  non-whitespace  character[m
[31m-#               is a `#'.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        multi-line text[m
[31m-#               A  logical  line starts with non-whitespace text. A[m
[31m-#               line that starts with whitespace continues a  logi-[m
[31m-#               cal line.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        The  pattern specifies an email address, a domain name, or[m
[31m-#        a domain name hierarchy, as described  in  section  "TABLE[m
[31m-#        LOOKUP".[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        The  result is of the form transport:nexthop and specifies[m
[31m-#        how or where to deliver mail. This is described in section[m
[31m-#        "RESULT FORMAT".[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# TABLE SEARCH ORDER[m
[31m-#        With lookups from indexed files such as DB or DBM, or from[m
[31m-#        networked tables such as NIS, LDAP or  SQL,  patterns  are[m
[31m-#        tried in the order as listed below:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        user+extension@domain transport:nexthop[m
[31m-#               Deliver   mail  for  user+extension@domain  through[m
[31m-#               transport to nexthop.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        user@domain transport:nexthop[m
[31m-#               Deliver mail for user@domain through  transport  to[m
[31m-#               nexthop.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        domain transport:nexthop[m
[31m-#               Deliver  mail  for domain through transport to nex-[m
[31m-#               thop.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        .domain transport:nexthop[m
[31m-#               Deliver mail for any subdomain  of  domain  through[m
[31m-#               transport  to  nexthop.  This applies only when the[m
[31m-#               string transport_maps is not  listed  in  the  par-[m
[31m-#               ent_domain_matches_subdomains   configuration  set-[m
[31m-#               ting.  Otherwise, a domain name matches itself  and[m
[31m-#               its subdomains.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        * transport:nexthop[m
[31m-#               The  special pattern * represents any address (i.e.[m
[31m-#               it functions  as  the  wild-card  pattern,  and  is[m
[31m-#               unique to Postfix transport tables).[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Note  1:  the  null  recipient  address  is  looked  up as[m
[31m-#        $empty_address_recipient@$myhostname (default: mailer-dae-[m
[31m-#        mon@hostname).[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Note  2:  user@domain  or  user+extension@domain lookup is[m
[31m-#        available in Postfix 2.0 and later.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# RESULT FORMAT[m
[31m-#        The lookup result is of the form  transport:nexthop.   The[m
[31m-#        transport  field  specifies a mail delivery transport such[m
[31m-#        as smtp or local. The nexthop field  specifies  where  and[m
[31m-#        how to deliver mail.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        The  transport field specifies the name of a mail delivery[m
[31m-#        transport (the first name of a mail delivery service entry[m
[31m-#        in the Postfix master.cf file).[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        The  interpretation  of  the  nexthop  field  is transport[m
[31m-#        dependent. In the case of SMTP, specify  a  service  on  a[m
[31m-#        non-default  port  as  host:service,  and disable MX (mail[m
[31m-#        exchanger) DNS lookups with [host] or [host]:port. The  [][m
[31m-#        form is required when you specify an IP address instead of[m
[31m-#        a hostname.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        A null transport and null nexthop  result  means  "do  not[m
[31m-#        change":  use  the delivery transport and nexthop informa-[m
[31m-#        tion that would be used when the  entire  transport  table[m
[31m-#        did not exist.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        A  non-null  transport  field  with  a  null nexthop field[m
[31m-#        resets the nexthop information to the recipient domain.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        A null transport field with non-null  nexthop  field  does[m
[31m-#        not modify the transport information.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# EXAMPLES[m
[31m-#        In  order to deliver internal mail directly, while using a[m
[31m-#        mail relay for all other mail, specify a  null  entry  for[m
[31m-#        internal  destinations  (do not change the delivery trans-[m
[31m-#        port or the nexthop information) and  specify  a  wildcard[m
[31m-#        for all other destinations.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#             my.domain    :[m
[31m-#             .my.domain   :[m
[31m-#             *            smtp:outbound-relay.my.domain[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        In  order  to send mail for example.com and its subdomains[m
[31m-#        via the uucp transport to the UUCP host named example:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#             example.com      uucp:example[m
[31m-#             .example.com     uucp:example[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        When no nexthop host name is  specified,  the  destination[m
[31m-#        domain  name  is  used instead. For example, the following[m
[31m-#        directs mail for user@example.com via the  slow  transport[m
[31m-#        to  a  mail exchanger for example.com.  The slow transport[m
[31m-#        could be configured to run at most one delivery process at[m
[31m-#        a time:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#             example.com      slow:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        When no transport is specified, Postfix uses the transport[m
[31m-#        that matches the address  domain  class  (see  DESCRIPTION[m
[31m-#        above).   The following sends all mail for example.com and[m
[31m-#        its subdomains to host gateway.example.com:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#             example.com      :[gateway.example.com][m
[31m-#             .example.com     :[gateway.example.com][m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        In the above example, the [] suppress  MX  lookups.   This[m
[31m-#        prevents  mail  routing loops when your machine is primary[m
[31m-#        MX host for example.com.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        In the case of delivery via SMTP, one  may  specify  host-[m
[31m-#        name:service instead of just a host:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#             example.com      smtp:bar.example:2025[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        This directs mail for user@example.com to host bar.example[m
[31m-#        port 2025. Instead of a numerical port a symbolic name may[m
[31m-#        be used. Specify [] around the hostname if MX lookups must[m
[31m-#        be disabled.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        The error mailer can be used to bounce mail:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#             .example.com     error:mail for *.example.com is not deliverable[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        This causes all mail for user@anything.example.com  to  be[m
[31m-#        bounced.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# REGULAR EXPRESSION TABLES[m
[31m-#        This  section  describes how the table lookups change when[m
[31m-#        the table is given in the form of regular expressions. For[m
[31m-#        a  description  of regular expression lookup table syntax,[m
[31m-#        see regexp_table(5) or pcre_table(5).[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Each pattern is a regular expression that  is  applied  to[m
[31m-#        the    entire    address    being    looked    up.   Thus,[m
[31m-#        some.domain.hierarchy is not  looked  up  via  its  parent[m
[31m-#        domains,  nor is user+foo@domain looked up as user@domain.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Patterns are applied in the order as specified in the  ta-[m
[31m-#        ble,  until  a  pattern  is  found that matches the search[m
[31m-#        string.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        The trivial-rewrite(8) server disallows regular expression[m
[31m-#        substitution  of  $1  etc.  in  regular  expression lookup[m
[31m-#        tables, because that could open a security  hole  (Postfix[m
[31m-#        version 2.3 and later).[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# TCP-BASED TABLES[m
[31m-#        This  section  describes how the table lookups change when[m
[31m-#        lookups are directed to a TCP-based server. For a descrip-[m
[31m-#        tion of the TCP client/server lookup protocol, see tcp_ta-[m
[31m-#        ble(5).  This feature is not available up to and including[m
[31m-#        Postfix version 2.4.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Each  lookup  operation  uses the entire recipient address[m
[31m-#        once.  Thus, some.domain.hierarchy is not  looked  up  via[m
[31m-#        its  parent  domains,  nor is user+foo@domain looked up as[m
[31m-#        user@domain.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Results are the same as with indexed file lookups.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# CONFIGURATION PARAMETERS[m
[31m-#        The following main.cf parameters are especially  relevant.[m
[31m-#        The  text  below  provides  only  a parameter summary. See[m
[31m-#        postconf(5) for more details including examples.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        empty_address_recipient[m
[31m-#               The address that is looked up instead of  the  null[m
[31m-#               sender address.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        parent_domain_matches_subdomains[m
[31m-#               List  of  Postfix features that use domain.tld pat-[m
[31m-#               terns  to  match  sub.domain.tld  (as  opposed   to[m
[31m-#               requiring .domain.tld patterns).[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        transport_maps[m
[31m-#               List of transport lookup tables.[m
[31m-# [m
