[31m-# REJECTING MAIL FOR UNKNOWN LOCAL USERS[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The local_recipient_maps parameter specifies optional lookup tables[m
[31m-# with all names or addresses of users that are local with respect[m
[31m-# to $mydestination, $inet_interfaces or $proxy_interfaces.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# If this parameter is defined, then the SMTP server will reject[m
[31m-# mail for unknown local users. This parameter is defined by default.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# To turn off local recipient checking in the SMTP server, specify[m
[31m-# local_recipient_maps = (i.e. empty).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The default setting assumes that you use the default Postfix local[m
[31m-# delivery agent for local delivery. You need to update the[m
[31m-# local_recipient_maps setting if:[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# - You define $mydestination domain recipients in files other than[m
[31m-#   /etc/passwd, /etc/aliases, or the $virtual_alias_maps files.[m
[31m-#   For example, you define $mydestination domain recipients in    [m
[31m-#   the $virtual_mailbox_maps files.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# - You redefine the local delivery agent in master.cf.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# - You redefine the "local_transport" setting in main.cf.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# - You use the "luser_relay", "mailbox_transport", or "fallback_transport"[m
[31m-#   feature of the Postfix local delivery agent (see local(8)).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Details are described in the LOCAL_RECIPIENT_README file.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Beware: if the Postfix SMTP server runs chrooted, you probably have[m
[31m-# to access the passwd file via the proxymap service, in order to[m
[31m-# overcome chroot restrictions. The alternative, having a copy of[m
[31m-# the system passwd file in the chroot jail is just not practical.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The right-hand side of the lookup tables is conveniently ignored.[m
[31m-# In the left-hand side, specify a bare username, an @domain.tld[m
[31m-# wild-card, or specify a user@domain.tld address.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#local_recipient_maps = unix:passwd.byname $alias_maps[m
[31m-#local_recipient_maps = proxy:unix:passwd.byname $alias_maps[m
[31m-#local_recipient_maps =[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The unknown_local_recipient_reject_code specifies the SMTP server[m
[31m-# response code when a recipient domain matches $mydestination or[m
[31m-# ${proxy,inet}_interfaces, while $local_recipient_maps is non-empty[m
[31m-# and the recipient address or address local-part is not found.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The default setting is 550 (reject mail) but it is safer to start[m
[31m-# with 450 (try again later) until you are certain that your[m
[31m-# local_recipient_maps settings are OK.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-unknown_local_recipient_reject_code = 550[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# TRUST AND RELAY CONTROL[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The mynetworks parameter specifies the list of "trusted" SMTP[m
[31m-# clients that have more privileges than "strangers".[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# In particular, "trusted" SMTP clients are allowed to relay mail[m
[31m-# through Postfix.  See the smtpd_recipient_restrictions parameter[m
[31m-# in postconf(5).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# You can specify the list of "trusted" network addresses by hand[m
[31m-# or you can let Postfix do it for you (which is the default).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# By default (mynetworks_style = subnet), Postfix "trusts" SMTP[m
[31m-# clients in the same IP subnetworks as the local machine.[m
[31m-# On Linux, this does works correctly only with interfaces specified[m
[31m-# with the "ifconfig" command.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# Specify "mynetworks_style = class" when Postfix should "trust" SMTP[m
[31m-# clients in the same IP class A/B/C networks as the local machine.[m
[31m-# Don't do this with a dialup site - it would cause Postfix to "trust"[m
[31m-# your entire provider's network.  Instead, specify an explicit[m
[31m-# mynetworks list by hand, as described below.[m
[31m-#  [m
[31m-# Specify "mynetworks_style = host" when Postfix should "trust"[m
[31m-# only the local machine.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#mynetworks_style = class[m
[31m-#mynetworks_style = subnet[m
[31m-mynetworks_style = host[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# Alternatively, you can specify the mynetworks list by hand, in[m
[31m-# which case Postfix ignores the mynetworks_style setting.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Specify an explicit list of network/netmask patterns, where the[m
[31m-# mask specifies the number of bits in the network part of a host[m
[31m-# address.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# You can also specify the absolute pathname of a pattern file instead[m
[31m-# of listing the patterns here. Specify type:table for table-based lookups[m
[31m-# (the value on the table right-hand side is not used).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#mynetworks = 168.100.189.0/28, 127.0.0.0/8[m
[31m-#mynetworks = $config_directory/mynetworks[m
[31m-#mynetworks = hash:/etc/postfix/network_table[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The relay_domains parameter restricts what destinations this system will[m
[31m-# relay mail to.  See the smtpd_recipient_restrictions description in[m
[31m-# postconf(5) for detailed information.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# By default, Postfix relays mail[m
[31m-# - from "trusted" clients (IP address matches $mynetworks) to any destination,[m
[31m-# - from "untrusted" clients to destinations that match $relay_domains or[m
[31m-#   subdomains thereof, except addresses with sender-specified routing.[m
[31m-# The default relay_domains value is $mydestination.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# In addition to the above, the Postfix SMTP server by default accepts mail[m
[31m-# that Postfix is final destination for:[m
[31m-# - destinations that match $inet_interfaces or $proxy_interfaces,[m
[31m-# - destinations that match $mydestination[m
[31m-# - destinations that match $virtual_alias_domains,[m
[31m-# - destinations that match $virtual_mailbox_domains.[m
[31m-# These destinations do not need to be listed in $relay_domains.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# Specify a list of hosts or domains, /file/name patterns or type:name[m
[31m-# lookup tables, separated by commas and/or whitespace.  Continue[m
[31m-# long lines by starting the next line with whitespace. A file name[m
[31m-# is replaced by its contents; a type:name table is matched when a[m
[31m-# (parent) domain appears as lookup key.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# NOTE: Postfix will not automatically forward mail for domains that[m
[31m-# list this system as their primary or backup MX host. See the[m
[31m-# permit_mx_backup restriction description in postconf(5).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-relay_domains = $mydestination[m
[31m-virtual_alias_maps = hash:/etc/postfix/virtual[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# INTERNET OR INTRANET[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The relayhost parameter specifies the default host to send mail to[m
[31m-# when no entry is matched in the optional transport(5) table. When[m
[31m-# no relayhost is given, mail is routed directly to the destination.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# On an intranet, specify the organizational domain name. If your[m
[31m-# internal DNS uses no MX records, specify the name of the intranet[m
[31m-# gateway host instead.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# In the case of SMTP, specify a domain, host, host:port, [host]:port,[m
[31m-# [address] or [address]:port; the form [host] turns off MX lookups.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# If you're connected via UUCP, see also the default_transport parameter.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#relayhost = $mydomain[m
[31m-#relayhost = [gateway.my.domain][m
[31m-#relayhost = [mailserver.isp.tld][m
[31m-#relayhost = uucphost[m
[31m-#relayhost = [an.ip.add.ress][m
[31m-[m
[31m-# REJECTING UNKNOWN RELAY USERS[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The relay_recipient_maps parameter specifies optional lookup tables[m
[31m-# with all addresses in the domains that match $relay_domains.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# If this parameter is defined, then the SMTP server will reject[m
[31m-# mail for unknown relay users. This feature is off by default.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The right-hand side of the lookup tables is conveniently ignored.[m
[31m-# In the left-hand side, specify an @domain.tld wild-card, or specify[m
[31m-# a user@domain.tld address.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#relay_recipient_maps = hash:/etc/postfix/relay_recipients[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# INPUT RATE CONTROL[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The in_flow_delay configuration parameter implements mail input[m
[31m-# flow control. This feature is turned on by default, although it[m
[31m-# still needs further development (it's disabled on SCO UNIX due[m
[31m-# to an SCO bug).[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# A Postfix process will pause for $in_flow_delay seconds before[m
[31m-# accepting a new message, when the message arrival rate exceeds the[m
[31m-# message delivery rate. With the default 100 SMTP server process[m
[31m-# limit, this limits the mail inflow to 100 messages a second more[m
[31m-# than the number of messages delivered per second.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# Specify 0 to disable the feature. Valid delays are 0..10.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#in_flow_delay = 1s[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# ADDRESS REWRITING[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The ADDRESS_REWRITING_README document gives information about[m
[31m-# address masquerading or other forms of address rewriting including[m
[31m-# username->Firstname.Lastname mapping.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# ADDRESS REDIRECTION (VIRTUAL DOMAIN)[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The VIRTUAL_README document gives information about the many forms[m
[31m-# of domain hosting that Postfix supports.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# "USER HAS MOVED" BOUNCE MESSAGES[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# See the discussion in the ADDRESS_REWRITING_README document.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# TRANSPORT MAP[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# See the discussion in the ADDRESS_REWRITING_README document.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# ALIAS DATABASE[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The alias_maps parameter specifies the list of alias databases used[m
[31m-# by the local delivery agent. The default list is system dependent.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# On systems with NIS, the default is to search the local alias[m
[31m-# database, then the NIS alias database. See aliases(5) for syntax[m
[31m-# details.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# If you change the alias database, run "postalias /etc/aliases" (or[m
[31m-# wherever your system stores the mail alias file), or simply run[m
[31m-# "newaliases" to build the necessary DBM or DB file.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# It will take a minute or so before changes become visible.  Use[m
[31m-# "postfix reload" to eliminate the delay.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#alias_maps = dbm:/etc/aliases[m
[31m-alias_maps = hash:/etc/aliases[m
[31m-#alias_maps = hash:/etc/aliases, nis:mail.aliases[m
[31m-#alias_maps = netinfo:/aliases[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The alias_database parameter specifies the alias database(s) that[m
[31m-# are built with "newaliases" or "sendmail -bi".  This is a separate[m
[31m-# configuration parameter, because alias_maps (see above) may specify[m
[31m-# tables that are not necessarily all under control by Postfix.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#alias_database = dbm:/etc/aliases[m
[31m-#alias_database = dbm:/etc/mail/aliases[m
[31m-alias_database = hash:/etc/aliases[m
[31m-#alias_database = hash:/etc/aliases, hash:/opt/majordomo/aliases[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# ADDRESS EXTENSIONS (e.g., user+foo)[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The recipient_delimiter parameter specifies the separator between[m
[31m-# user names and address extensions (user+foo). See canonical(5),[m
[31m-# local(8), relocated(5) and virtual(5) for the effects this has on[m
[31m-# aliases, canonical, virtual, relocated and .forward file lookups.[m
[31m-# Basically, the software tries user+foo and .forward+foo before[m
[31m-# trying user and .forward.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#recipient_delimiter = +[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# DELIVERY TO MAILBOX[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The home_mailbox parameter specifies the optional pathname of a[m
[31m-# mailbox file relative to a user's home directory. The default[m
[31m-# mailbox file is /var/spool/mail/user or /var/mail/user.  Specify[m
[31m-# "Maildir/" for qmail-style delivery (the / is required).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#home_mailbox = Mailbox[m
[31m-#home_mailbox = Maildir/[m
[31m- [m
[31m-# The mail_spool_directory parameter specifies the directory where[m
[31m-# UNIX-style mailboxes are kept. The default setting depends on the[m
[31m-# system type.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#mail_spool_directory = /var/mail[m
[31m-#mail_spool_directory = /var/spool/mail[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The mailbox_command parameter specifies the optional external[m
[31m-# command to use instead of mailbox delivery. The command is run as[m
[31m-# the recipient with proper HOME, SHELL and LOGNAME environment settings.[m
[31m-# Exception:  delivery for root is done as $default_user.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Other environment variables of interest: USER (recipient username),[m
[31m-# EXTENSION (address extension), DOMAIN (domain part of address),[m
[31m-# and LOCAL (the address localpart).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Unlike other Postfix configuration parameters, the mailbox_command[m
[31m-# parameter is not subjected to $parameter substitutions. This is to[m
[31m-# make it easier to specify shell syntax (see example below).[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Avoid shell meta characters because they will force Postfix to run[m
[31m-# an expensive shell process. Procmail alone is expensive enough.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# IF YOU USE THIS TO DELIVER MAIL SYSTEM-WIDE, YOU MUST SET UP AN[m
[31m-# ALIAS THAT FORWARDS MAIL FOR ROOT TO A REAL USER.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#mailbox_command = /some/where/procmail[m
[31m-#mailbox_command = /some/where/procmail -a "$EXTENSION"[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The mailbox_transport specifies the optional transport in master.cf[m
[31m-# to use after processing aliases and .forward files. This parameter[m
[31m-# has precedence over the mailbox_command, fallback_transport and[m
[31m-# luser_relay parameters.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Specify a string of the form transport:nexthop, where transport is[m
[31m-# the name of a mail delivery transport defined in master.cf.  The[m
[31m-# :nexthop part is optional. For more details see the sample transport[m
[31m-# configuration file.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# NOTE: if you use this feature for accounts not in the UNIX password[m
[31m-# file, then you must update the "local_recipient_maps" setting in[m
[31m-# the main.cf file, otherwise the SMTP server will reject mail for    [m
[31m-# non-UNIX accounts with "User unknown in local recipient table".[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Cyrus IMAP over LMTP. Specify ``lmtpunix      cmd="lmtpd"[m
[31m-# listen="/var/imap/socket/lmtp" prefork=0'' in cyrus.conf.[m
[31m-#mailbox_transport = lmtp:unix:/var/lib/imap/socket/lmtp[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# If using the cyrus-imapd IMAP server deliver local mail to the IMAP[m
[31m-# server using LMTP (Local Mail Transport Protocol), this is prefered[m
[31m-# over the older cyrus deliver program by setting the[m
[31m-# mailbox_transport as below:[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# mailbox_transport = lmtp:unix:/var/lib/imap/socket/lmtp[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The efficiency of LMTP delivery for cyrus-imapd can be enhanced via[m
[31m-# these settings.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# local_destination_recipient_limit = 300[m
[31m-# local_destination_concurrency_limit = 5[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Of course you should adjust these settings as appropriate for the[m
[31m-# capacity of the hardware you are using. The recipient limit setting[m
[31m-# can be used to take advantage of the single instance message store[m
[31m-# capability of Cyrus. The concurrency limit can be used to control[m
[31m-# how many simultaneous LMTP sessions will be permitted to the Cyrus[m
[31m-# message store. [m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Cyrus IMAP via command line. Uncomment the "cyrus...pipe" and[m
[31m-# subsequent line in master.cf.[m
[31m-mailbox_transport = cyrus[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The fallback_transport specifies the optional transport in master.cf[m
[31m-# to use for recipients that are not found in the UNIX passwd database.[m
[31m-# This parameter has precedence over the luser_relay parameter.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Specify a string of the form transport:nexthop, where transport is[m
[31m-# the name of a mail delivery transport defined in master.cf.  The[m
[31m-# :nexthop part is optional. For more details see the sample transport[m
[31m-# configuration file.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# NOTE: if you use this feature for accounts not in the UNIX password[m
[31m-# file, then you must update the "local_recipient_maps" setting in[m
[31m-# the main.cf file, otherwise the SMTP server will reject mail for    [m
[31m-# non-UNIX accounts with "User unknown in local recipient table".[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#fallback_transport = lmtp:unix:/var/lib/imap/socket/lmtp[m
[31m-#fallback_transport =[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The luser_relay parameter specifies an optional destination address[m
[31m-# for unknown recipients.  By default, mail for unknown@$mydestination,[m
[31m-# unknown@[$inet_interfaces] or unknown@[$proxy_interfaces] is returned[m
[31m-# as undeliverable.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The following expansions are done on luser_relay: $user (recipient[m
[31m-# username), $shell (recipient shell), $home (recipient home directory),[m
[31m-# $recipient (full recipient address), $extension (recipient address[m
[31m-# extension), $domain (recipient domain), $local (entire recipient[m
[31m-# localpart), $recipient_delimiter. Specify ${name?value} or[m
[31m-# ${name:value} to expand value only when $name does (does not) exist.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# luser_relay works only for the default Postfix local delivery agent.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# NOTE: if you use this feature for accounts not in the UNIX password[m
[31m-# file, then you must specify "local_recipient_maps =" (i.e. empty) in[m
[31m-# the main.cf file, otherwise the SMTP server will reject mail for    [m
[31m-# non-UNIX accounts with "User unknown in local recipient table".[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#luser_relay = $user@other.host[m
[31m-#luser_relay = $local@other.host[m
[31m-#luser_relay = admin+$local[m
[31m-  [m
[31m-# JUNK MAIL CONTROLS[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# The controls listed here are only a very small subset. The file[m
[31m-# SMTPD_ACCESS_README provides an overview.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The header_checks parameter specifies an optional table with patterns[m
[31m-# that each logical message header is matched against, including[m
[31m-# headers that span multiple physical lines.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# By default, these patterns also apply to MIME headers and to the[m
[31m-# headers of attached messages. With older Postfix versions, MIME and[m
[31m-# attached message headers were treated as body text.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# For details, see "man header_checks".[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#header_checks = regexp:/etc/postfix/header_checks[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# FAST ETRN SERVICE[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Postfix maintains per-destination logfiles with information about[m
[31m-# deferred mail, so that mail can be flushed quickly with the SMTP[m
[31m-# "ETRN domain.tld" command, or by executing "sendmail -qRdomain.tld".[m
[31m-# See the ETRN_README document for a detailed description.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# The fast_flush_domains parameter controls what destinations are[m
[31m-# eligible for this service. By default, they are all domains that[m
[31m-# this server is willing to relay mail to.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#fast_flush_domains = $relay_domains[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# SHOW SOFTWARE VERSION OR NOT[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The smtpd_banner parameter specifies the text that follows the 220[m
[31m-# code in the SMTP server's greeting banner. Some people like to see[m
[31m-# the mail version advertised. By default, Postfix shows no version.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# You MUST specify $myhostname at the start of the text. That is an[m
[31m-# RFC requirement. Postfix itself does not care.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#smtpd_banner = $myhostname ESMTP $mail_name[m
[31m-#smtpd_banner = $myhostname ESMTP $mail_name ($mail_version)[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# PARALLEL DELIVERY TO THE SAME DESTINATION[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# How many parallel deliveries to the same user or domain? With local[m
[31m-# delivery, it does not make sense to do massively parallel delivery[m
[31m-# to the same user, because mailbox updates must happen sequentially,[m
[31m-# and expensive pipelines in .forward files can cause disasters when[m
[31m-# too many are run at the same time. With SMTP deliveries, 10[m
[31m-# simultaneous connections to the same domain could be sufficient to[m
[31m-# raise eyebrows.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# Each message delivery transport has its XXX_destination_concurrency_limit[m
[31m-# parameter.  The default is $default_destination_concurrency_limit for[m
[31m-# most delivery transports. For the local delivery agent the default is 2.[m
[31m-[m
[31m-#local_destination_concurrency_limit = 2[m
[31m-#default_destination_concurrency_limit = 20[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# DEBUGGING CONTROL[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# The debug_peer_level parameter specifies the increment in verbose[m
[31m-# logging level when an SMTP client or server host name or address[m
[31m-# matches a pattern in the debug_peer_list parameter.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-debug_peer_level = 2[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The debug_peer_list parameter specifies an optional list of domain[m
[31m-# or network patterns, /file/name patterns or type:name tables. When[m
[31m-# an SMTP client or server host name or address matches a pattern,[m
[31m-# increase the verbose logging level by the amount specified in the[m
[31m-# debug_peer_level parameter.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-#debug_peer_list = 127.0.0.1[m
[31m-#debug_peer_list = some.domain[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# The debugger_command specifies the external command that is executed[m
[31m-# when a Postfix daemon program is run with the -D option.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Use "command .. & sleep 5" so that the debugger can attach before[m
[31m-# the process marches on. If you use an X-based debugger, be sure to[m
[31m-# set up your XAUTHORITY environment variable before starting Postfix.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-debugger_command =[m
[31m-	 PATH=/bin:/usr/bin:/usr/local/bin:/usr/X11R6/bin[m
[31m-	 ddd $daemon_directory/$process_name $process_id & sleep 5[m
[31m-[m
[31m-# If you can't use X, use this to capture the call stack when a[m
[31m-# daemon crashes. The result is in a file in the configuration[m
[31m-# directory, and is named after the process name and the process ID.[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# debugger_command =[m
[31m-#	PATH=/bin:/usr/bin:/usr/local/bin; export PATH; (echo cont;[m
[31m-#	echo where) | gdb $daemon_directory/$process_name $process_id 2>&1[m
[31m-#	>$config_directory/$process_name.$process_id.log & sleep 5[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# Another possibility is to run gdb under a detached screen session.[m
[31m-# To attach to the screen sesssion, su root and run "screen -r[m
[31m-# <id_string>" where <id_string> uniquely matches one of the detached[m
[31m-# sessions (from "screen -list").[m
[31m-#[m
[31m-# debugger_command =[m
[31m-#	PATH=/bin:/usr/bin:/sbin:/usr/sbin; export PATH; screen[m
[31m-#	-dmS $process_name gdb $daemon_directory/$process_name[m
[31m-#	$process_id & sleep 1[m
[31m-[m
