[31m-# VIRTUAL(5)                                                          VIRTUAL(5)[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# NAME[m
[31m-#        virtual - Postfix virtual alias table format[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# SYNOPSIS[m
[31m-#        postmap /etc/postfix/virtual[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        postmap -q "string" /etc/postfix/virtual[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        postmap -q - /etc/postfix/virtual <inputfile[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# DESCRIPTION[m
[31m-#        The  optional  virtual(5)  alias  table rewrites recipient[m
[31m-#        addresses for all local, all virtual, and all remote  mail[m
[31m-#        destinations.   This  is unlike the aliases(5) table which[m
[31m-#        is used only for local(8) delivery.  Virtual  aliasing  is[m
[31m-#        recursive,  and  is  implemented by the Postfix cleanup(8)[m
[31m-#        daemon before mail is queued.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        The main applications of virtual aliasing are:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        o      To redirect mail for one address  to  one  or  more[m
[31m-#               addresses.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        o      To   implement  virtual  alias  domains  where  all[m
[31m-#               addresses  are  aliased  to  addresses   in   other[m
[31m-#               domains.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#               Virtual  alias  domains are not to be confused with[m
[31m-#               the virtual mailbox domains  that  are  implemented[m
[31m-#               with  the  Postfix  virtual(8) mail delivery agent.[m
[31m-#               With  virtual  mailbox  domains,   each   recipient[m
[31m-#               address can have its own mailbox.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Virtual  aliasing  is  applied  only to recipient envelope[m
[31m-#        addresses, and  does  not  affect  message  headers.   Use[m
[31m-#        canonical(5)   mapping  to  rewrite  header  and  envelope[m
[31m-#        addresses in general.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Normally, the virtual(5) alias table  is  specified  as  a[m
[31m-#        text  file that serves as input to the postmap(1) command.[m
[31m-#        The result, an indexed file in dbm or db format,  is  used[m
[31m-#        for fast searching by the mail system. Execute the command[m
[31m-#        "postmap /etc/postfix/virtual" to rebuild an indexed  file[m
[31m-#        after changing the corresponding text file.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        When  the  table  is provided via other means such as NIS,[m
[31m-#        LDAP or SQL, the same lookups are  done  as  for  ordinary[m
[31m-#        indexed files.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Alternatively,  the  table  can  be provided as a regular-[m
[31m-#        expression map where patterns are given as regular expres-[m
[31m-#        sions,  or lookups can be directed to TCP-based server. In[m
[31m-#        those case, the lookups are done in a  slightly  different[m
[31m-#        way  as  described below under "REGULAR EXPRESSION TABLES"[m
[31m-#        or "TCP-BASED TABLES".[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# CASE FOLDING[m
[31m-#        The search string is folded to lowercase  before  database[m
[31m-#        lookup.  As  of Postfix 2.3, the search string is not case[m
[31m-#        folded with database types such as regexp: or pcre:  whose[m
[31m-#        lookup fields can match both upper and lower case.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# TABLE FORMAT[m
[31m-#        The input format for the postmap(1) command is as follows:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        pattern result[m
[31m-#               When pattern matches a mail address, replace it  by[m
[31m-#               the corresponding result.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        blank lines and comments[m
[31m-#               Empty  lines and whitespace-only lines are ignored,[m
[31m-#               as are lines whose first  non-whitespace  character[m
[31m-#               is a `#'.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        multi-line text[m
[31m-#               A  logical  line starts with non-whitespace text. A[m
[31m-#               line that starts with whitespace continues a  logi-[m
[31m-#               cal line.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# TABLE SEARCH ORDER[m
[31m-#        With lookups from indexed files such as DB or DBM, or from[m
[31m-#        networked tables such as NIS, LDAP or  SQL,  patterns  are[m
[31m-#        tried in the order as listed below:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        user@domain address, address, ...[m
[31m-#               Redirect  mail  for  user@domain  to address.  This[m
[31m-#               form has the highest precedence.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        user address, address, ...[m
[31m-#               Redirect mail for user@site to address when site is[m
[31m-#               equal  to $myorigin, when site is listed in $mydes-[m
[31m-#               tination, or when it is listed in  $inet_interfaces[m
[31m-#               or $proxy_interfaces.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#               This  functionality  overlaps with functionality of[m
[31m-#               the local aliases(5) database.  The  difference  is[m
[31m-#               that virtual(5) mapping can be applied to non-local[m
[31m-#               addresses.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        @domain address, address, ...[m
[31m-#               Redirect mail for other users in domain to address.[m
[31m-#               This form has the lowest precedence.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#               Note:  @domain  is a wild-card. With this form, the[m
[31m-#               Postfix SMTP server accepts mail for any  recipient[m
[31m-#               in  domain,  regardless  of  whether that recipient[m
[31m-#               exists.  This may turn  your  mail  system  into  a[m
[31m-#               backscatter  source: Postfix first accepts mail for[m
[31m-#               non-existent recipients and then  tries  to  return[m
[31m-#               that  mail  as  "undeliverable" to the often forged[m
[31m-#               sender address.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# RESULT ADDRESS REWRITING[m
[31m-#        The lookup result is subject to address rewriting:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        o      When the result  has  the  form  @otherdomain,  the[m
[31m-#               result  becomes the same user in otherdomain.  This[m
[31m-#               works only for the first address in a multi-address[m
[31m-#               lookup result.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        o      When  "append_at_myorigin=yes", append "@$myorigin"[m
[31m-#               to addresses without "@domain".[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        o      When "append_dot_mydomain=yes", append ".$mydomain"[m
[31m-#               to addresses without ".domain".[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# ADDRESS EXTENSION[m
[31m-#        When a mail address localpart contains the optional recip-[m
[31m-#        ient delimiter (e.g., user+foo@domain), the  lookup  order[m
[31m-#        becomes: user+foo@domain, user@domain, user+foo, user, and[m
[31m-#        @domain.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        The  propagate_unmatched_extensions   parameter   controls[m
[31m-#        whether  an  unmatched  address extension (+foo) is propa-[m
[31m-#        gated to the result of table lookup.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# VIRTUAL ALIAS DOMAINS[m
[31m-#        Besides virtual aliases, the virtual alias table can  also[m
[31m-#        be used to implement virtual alias domains. With a virtual[m
[31m-#        alias domain,  all  recipient  addresses  are  aliased  to[m
[31m-#        addresses in other domains.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Virtual alias domains are not to be confused with the vir-[m
[31m-#        tual mailbox domains that are implemented with the Postfix[m
[31m-#        virtual(8)  mail  delivery  agent.  With  virtual  mailbox[m
[31m-#        domains, each recipient address can have its own  mailbox.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        With  a  virtual  alias domain, the virtual domain has its[m
[31m-#        own user name space. Local  (i.e.  non-virtual)  usernames[m
[31m-#        are  not visible in a virtual alias domain. In particular,[m
[31m-#        local aliases(5) and local mailing lists are  not  visible[m
[31m-#        as localname@virtual-alias.domain.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Support for a virtual alias domain looks like:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        /etc/postfix/main.cf:[m
[31m-#            virtual_alias_maps = hash:/etc/postfix/virtual[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Note: some systems use dbm databases instead of hash.  See[m
[31m-#        the output  from  "postconf  -m"  for  available  database[m
[31m-#        types.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        /etc/postfix/virtual:[m
[31m-#            virtual-alias.domain     anything (right-hand content does not matter)[m
[31m-#            postmaster@virtual-alias.domain  postmaster[m
[31m-#            user1@virtual-alias.domain       address1[m
[31m-#            user2@virtual-alias.domain       address2, address3[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        The  virtual-alias.domain anything entry is required for a[m
[31m-#        virtual alias domain. Without this entry, mail is rejected[m
[31m-#        with  "relay  access  denied", or bounces with "mail loops[m
[31m-#        back to myself".[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Do not specify virtual alias domain names in  the  main.cf[m
[31m-#        mydestination or relay_domains configuration parameters.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        With  a  virtual  alias  domain,  the  Postfix SMTP server[m
[31m-#        accepts  mail  for  known-user@virtual-alias.domain,   and[m
[31m-#        rejects   mail  for  unknown-user@virtual-alias.domain  as[m
[31m-#        undeliverable.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Instead of specifying the virtual alias  domain  name  via[m
[31m-#        the  virtual_alias_maps table, you may also specify it via[m
[31m-#        the main.cf virtual_alias_domains configuration parameter.[m
[31m-#        This  latter parameter uses the same syntax as the main.cf[m
[31m-#        mydestination configuration parameter.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# REGULAR EXPRESSION TABLES[m
[31m-#        This section describes how the table lookups  change  when[m
[31m-#        the table is given in the form of regular expressions. For[m
[31m-#        a description of regular expression lookup  table  syntax,[m
[31m-#        see regexp_table(5) or pcre_table(5).[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Each  pattern  is  a regular expression that is applied to[m
[31m-#        the entire address being looked up. Thus, user@domain mail[m
[31m-#        addresses  are  not  broken up into their user and @domain[m
[31m-#        constituent parts, nor is user+foo broken up into user and[m
[31m-#        foo.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Patterns  are applied in the order as specified in the ta-[m
[31m-#        ble, until a pattern is  found  that  matches  the  search[m
[31m-#        string.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Results  are  the  same as with indexed file lookups, with[m
[31m-#        the additional feature that parenthesized substrings  from[m
[31m-#        the pattern can be interpolated as $1, $2 and so on.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# TCP-BASED TABLES[m
[31m-#        This  section  describes how the table lookups change when[m
[31m-#        lookups are directed to a TCP-based server. For a descrip-[m
[31m-#        tion of the TCP client/server lookup protocol, see tcp_ta-[m
[31m-#        ble(5).  This feature is not available up to and including[m
[31m-#        Postfix version 2.4.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Each lookup operation uses the entire address once.  Thus,[m
[31m-#        user@domain mail addresses are not broken  up  into  their[m
[31m-#        user and @domain constituent parts, nor is user+foo broken[m
[31m-#        up into user and foo.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Results are the same as with indexed file lookups.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# BUGS[m
[31m-#        The table format does not understand quoting  conventions.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# CONFIGURATION PARAMETERS[m
[31m-#        The  following  main.cf parameters are especially relevant[m
[31m-#        to this topic. See the Postfix  main.cf  file  for  syntax[m
[31m-#        details  and  for default values. Use the "postfix reload"[m
[31m-#        command after a configuration change.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        virtual_alias_maps[m
[31m-#               List of virtual aliasing tables.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        virtual_alias_domains[m
[31m-#               List of virtual alias domains. This uses  the  same[m
[31m-#               syntax as the mydestination parameter.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        propagate_unmatched_extensions[m
[31m-#               A  list  of  address rewriting or forwarding mecha-[m
[31m-#               nisms that propagate an address extension from  the[m
[31m-#               original  address  to  the result.  Specify zero or[m
[31m-#               more  of  canonical,   virtual,   alias,   forward,[m
[31m-#               include, or generic.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        Other parameters of interest:[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        inet_interfaces[m
[31m-#               The  network  interface  addresses that this system[m
[31m-#               receives mail on.  You need to stop and start Post-[m
[31m-#               fix when this parameter changes.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        mydestination[m
[31m-#               List  of  domains  that  this mail system considers[m
[31m-#               local.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        myorigin[m
[31m-#               The domain that is appended  to  any  address  that[m
[31m-#               does not have a domain.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        owner_request_special[m
[31m-#               Give special treatment to owner-xxx and xxx-request[m
[31m-#               addresses.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-#        proxy_interfaces[m
[31m-#               Other interfaces that this machine receives mail on[m
[31m-#               by way of a proxy agent or network address transla-[m
[31m-#               tor.[m
[31m-# [m
[31m-# SEE ALSO[m
[31m-#        cleanup(8), canonicalize and enqueue mail[m
